   "source": [
    "### Comments on Missingness\n",
    "Overall, missingness is present across datasets but can be addressed through targeted, defensible decisions.\n",
    "#### Wyscout\n",
    "No missingness observed.\n",
    "#### Skillcorner GI\n",
    "About 1.5% missingness across several metrics corresponds exactly to observations where `GI_CHECKED_PASS = FALSE`, indicating that tracking data for these rows is not reliably available.\n",
    "\n",
    "The higher missingness (~8.7%) in `offballrun_avgdistance` is largely driven by players (ie. defenders, goalkeepers) who do not generate off-ball run events, making the metric undefined. Restricting the sample to attacking players reduces missingness to ~1.4%, confirming this interpretation.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given the goal of identifying reliable recruitment targets, observations lacking validated tracking data will be removed to ensure all evaluated players are supported by complete and consistent information.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Skillcorner Physial\n",
    "Several \"Time to\" metrics (Time to Sprint post-COD, Time to Sprint, Time to HSR post-COD, Time to 505 around 180, Time to HSR) exhibit substantial missingness (25–70%).\n",
    "\n",
    "Given their limited coverage and the availability of alternative, similar proxies (e.g., acceleration metrics, 505 around 90, HSR-related features), these columns will be excluded from the analysis to avoid introducing noise and selection bias.\n",
    "\n",
    "After restricting to attacking players, the remaining missingness is minimal. Notably, `Time to 505 around 90` exhibits ~2.3% missingness. This is critical as the primary proxy for agility in the absence of `Time to 505 around 180`, so the feature will be retained and missing values are imputed using the median to ensure robustness while preserving its analytical value."
   ]
  },
